1. Introduction to chosen dataset

The chosen dataset comes from Integrated functional genomic analyses of Klinefelter and Turner syndromes reveal global network effects of altered X chromosome dosage which was published in February, 2020 by Zhang et. al.The authors of this paper were interested in differential expression between control individuals and individuals either Klinefelter or Turner syndrom (KS and TS, respectively). KS occurs in males when they are born with an extra X chromosome (i.e.XXY). On the other hand, TS occurs in females when they are born missing an X chromosome (i.e.XO).

3. Clean the data

# The original downloaded data as counts for each individual are stored in 
# separate files. Each file has these coloumns: gene_id, transcript_ids, length,
# effective_length, expected_count, TPM, and FPKM. Combine all the data files
# into one count matrix where each row is the gene, each column is the sample,
# and each cell stores the expected_count for the gene in that sample. 

# A helper function: add a sample name column to the dataframe that is stored
# at the given file path
add_name_to_counts <- function(file_path, sample_name) {
  df <- fread(file_path, select = c("gene_id", "expected_count"))
  df$sample <- sample_name
  return(df)
}

# Check if this step has already been done
if (file.exists("data/original_combined_counts.rds")) {
  combined_counts <- readRDS("data/original_combined_counts.rds")
} else {
  # List all the count files (should have 54 since there are 54 donors in the study)
  count_files <- list.files(dest_dir, 
                            pattern = "genes.results.txt.gz$", 
                            full.names = TRUE)
  
  # Initialize an empty list to store multiple data frames
  df_list <- list()
  
  # Loop through each file, read, and store in list
  for (file_path in count_files) {
    sample_name <- gsub(".*_(.*)\\.genes\\.results\\.txt\\.gz$", 
                        "\\1", 
                        basename(file_path))
    df_list[[sample_name]] <- add_name_to_counts(file_path, 
                                                 sample_name)
  }
  
  # Combine all data.tables into one 
  combined_df <- rbindlist(df_list, 
                           use.names = TRUE, 
                           fill = TRUE)
  
  # Reshape to wide format and convert to a matrix
  wide_df <- dcast(combined_df, gene_id ~ sample, value.var = "expected_count")
  row.names(wide_df) <- wide_df$gene_id
  
  # Remove the gene coloumn and adds gene names as rownames in the matrix
  combined_counts <- data.matrix(wide_df[, -1], )
  row.names(combined_counts) <- wide_df$gene_id
  
  saveRDS(combined_counts, "data/original_combined_counts.rds")
}

# The gene names are already mapped to HUGO gene symbols, but they are combined
# with the Ensembl gene identifiers (e.g. ensemblID_HUGO) Extract the HUGO gene 
# symbols and make these gene symbols the row names in the counts matrix
current_row_names <- rownames(combined_counts)
HUGO_names <- sapply(strsplit(current_row_names, "_", fixed = TRUE), 
                     function(x) x[2])
ensembl_ids_version <- sapply(strsplit(current_row_names, "_", fixed = TRUE),
                              function(x) x[1])
ensembl_ids <- sapply(ensembl_ids_version, function(x) sub("\\..*", "", x))


# Manually convert the ensembl gene IDs to the HUGO gene symbol 
# Use the ensembl gene IDs without the version to avoid filtering more genes
conversion_stash <- "data/id_conversion.rds"

ensembl <- useDataset("hsapiens_gene_ensembl", mart = useMart("ensembl"))

if (file.exists(conversion_stash)) {
  id_conversion <- readRDS(conversion_stash)
} else {
  id_conversion <- getBM(attributes = c("ensembl_gene_id", "hgnc_symbol"),
                         filters = c("ensembl_gene_id"), 
                         values = ensembl_ids, 
                         mart = ensembl)
  saveRDS(id_conversion, conversion_stash)
}

# Convert the counts matrix into a data frame object for now

5. Interpret and document

  1. Why is the dataset of interest to you? The dataset is of interest to me because I think it can provide insights into how the X chromosome impacts gene expression. In TS, individuals are missing one X chromosome, while in KS, individuals have an extra X chromosome. If there is differential expression between controls and individuals with KS or TS, we might predict that the X chromosome has an impact (e.g.regulates) on the genes that are differentially expressed. Further, it would also be interesting to determine if the differences in X chromosome copy number correlate with changes in gene expression for genes on not only the X chromosome, but also autosomal genes.

  2. What are the control and test conditions of the dataset? The are two control groups: healthy males and healthy females. Similarly, there are two test condition groups: females with Turners Syndrome and males with Klienfelters Syndrome. It would make sense to differential expression between the control males and the males with KS, or between the control females and the females with TS.

  3. How many samples in each of the conditions of your dataset? There are 14 females with TS, 14 female controls, 13 males with KS, and 13 male controls.

  4. Were there expression values that could not be mapped to current HUGO symbols? The original dataset had already been mapped to HUGO symbols. However, there were some HUGO symbols that appeared inaccurate. For example, there was a gene with the symbol Y in the original dataset. There were also some genes that did not seem to follow normal HUGO numenclature, such as only including uppercase characters. For that reason, I manually determined HUGO symbols using the biomaRt package. Then, I filtered the data to only include the genes where the original HUGO symbols and the manually determined HUGO symbols matched. This removed about 20000 genes out of 60498.

  5. Were there expression values that were not unique for specific genes? How did you handle these? After filtering out genes without HUGO symbols, there were 3 genes that appeared twice. However, for all 3 genes, one row would be 0 for all samples. Therefore, I did not remove these genes, but when I filtered the data based on low counts, these rows were removed.

  6. Were there any outliers in your dataset? How were they handled in the originating paper? How many outliers were removed? There were some outliers in the dataset that can be seen in the boxplots. However, each individual had at least a couple outliers, so for that reason no outlier genes were removed. In the original paper, no outliers were removed either.

  7. How did you handle replicates? There were no technical replicates in the dataset. There are a total of 54 samples and each sample came from a different individual. Samples were normalized using TMM.

  8. What is the final coverage of your dataset? There were 60498 genes to begin with, but after filtering out genes did not have HUGO gene symbols, and genes there were not expressed at more than 1 count per million (CPM) in at least 3 samples, there were 13458 genes left, making the coverage 22%.
